ContentClassification.TableDescription: 1985-90 Basic Table – Male. Basis: Age Last Birthday Before Revision. Minimum Select Age: 0. Maximum Select Age: 99. Minimum Ultimate Age: 25. Maximum Ultimate Age: 124
ContentClassification.Comments: Study Data: Society of Actuaries (SOA) intercompany mortality study on Standard Ordinary issues in the United States observed from 1985 to 1990 policy anniversaries. The total dollar amount of exposure was $3.5 trillion and the total claims amounted to $16.1 billion for males; the corresponding figures for the females being $1.07 trillion and $1.51 billion respectively. Medical, nonmedical and paramedical issues combined. Raw data was initially submitted using a 15-year select period. Later in the table construction process, the select data was re-submitted in a 25-year select period format. Methodology: Built from age nearest birthday tables (See SOA Table Identities 365 and 367). Ultimate developed from an average of q(x) and q(x+1). Select developed from formula: q'([x]+t)=(C)q([x]+t) + (1-C)q([x+1]+t) where C=.85 for age 0, .75 for 1, .875 for 2-4, .9 for 5-69. For ages 70 and over, the prescribed formula of the memo was not used but instead the rates were set equal to the age nearest birthday rates. NOTE: Subsequent to creation of this table and loading into MORT, the SOA released a memo stating that the formula for developing age last birthday rates from age nearest birthday rates had changed. This table represents the data as it appeared on the SOA’s website PRIOR TO the change in the formula. The values currently on the SOA Experience Studies web page reflect the change in methodology and are contained in tables 2012 and 2013. Data Transcription Errors: None. Data Certified: 07/2013
